x4freetext: Experiment was performed at the Los
Alamos Neutron Science Center Weapons Neutron Research
Target consisted of a
polystyrene capsule, 2.3 cm in diameter and 0.5 cm
thick, containing 2.2 grams of Tl oxide powder. The
Tl powder was tightly encapsulated in the thin-
walled capsule with an inner diameter of 2.2 cm.
Gamma rays produced in the bombardment of the
203Tl target by neutrons were observed with the
Germanium Array for Neutron-Induced Excitations
GEANIE located around 203Tl target. GEANIE was
comprised of 11 Compton-suppressed planar Ge
detectors (low-energy photon spectrometers, LEPS) ,
nine Compton-suppressed coaxial Ge detectors and six
unsuppressed coaxial Ge detectors.
Neutron energy was determined by time of
flight. Time structure of driving proton beam
consisted of 775 mu-s long macropulses. Each
macropulse consisted of subnanosecond micropulses
separated by 1.8 mu-s. Tl target was located on 20.34
m flight path 60degR
Neutrons were produced in a tungsten
spallation target driven by an 800 MeV proton beam.
Statistical uncertainty
Systematic uncertainty
